Media notes:
Close mic'ing of a Carolina Wren nest over the front door. There is evidence that they are already nesting. These calls could be the female or a juvenile within the nest. If a juvenile, I would think that there would be more than one calling. The ME 66 had a Rycote SuperSoftie attached and could have looked threatening.
 Same individuals as in ML539355.
 
 If anyone knows what the dove-like cooing is at the head of the cut, please let me know. Other Behaviors: Emit Distress Calls. Equipment Notes: Recorder's HPF on (80Hz, -18dB/octave). Elevation: 176 m.

Recorder: Voice Record Pro on iPhone 13 Pro
Media notes: Bird calling low in the underbrush, giving "cheer" notes and scolds.  I did not see the bird at all until the very end of the recording, when it flew out and crossed the trail.  Normalized to -3 dB except for voice announcement at -10 dB. 24-bit/48 kHz WAV file edited with Ocenaudio. Unfiltered.

Behavior and other notes: An adult Carolina Wren scolding near the feeders. Recording Time: 1107 (UTC -5).  Temperature 5.4C.  Habitat: mixed deciduous woods.  Distance to sound source: 8 meters.  Specific location: Wood Song, Berkeley Co., WV. Latitude 39.575464, Longitude -78.056623.  Elevation 156 meters.  ID’d by sight and sound; ID confidence 100%.  Equipment notes: Recorder HPF on at 80Hz, -18dB/octave. Recordists original file name: WH20T-019_Wood Song_ME66 at feeders_CARW chatter_Berkeley Co WV.wav

Female Carolina Wren calling from near front of house after just leaving the nest. Male giving calls in second example of female chatter calls.
 Same individuals as in ML539355. Equipment Notes: SD 702 HPF on (80Hz, -12dB/octave).

Scolding calls in response to playback from what turned out to be a female, based on response to playback of song (ML214304701). Mostly calling from mid-height in a tree after ascending from lower vegetation.

Calls from a single individual low in goldenrod off path, calling in response to pishing. At 2:46 switched to cheer calls, then at 3:18 to soft song intersperced with high-pitched, tree sparrow -like notes similar to those given by the pair in ML190199431.

Locality: D & H Rail Trail--Castleton to South St.
